</instruction>

explanation:
The report is correct. In metal_irq_allocate the local pointer cntr is only used to read members (cntr->irq_base and cntr->irq_num); the code never modifies the pointed-to object through cntr. According to MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 a pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible, so cntr should be declared as
    const struct metal_irq_controller *cntr;
This is safe: assigning the result of metal_container_of (a non-const pointer) to a pointer-to-const is allowed (adding const). The change enforces const-correctness locally and does not prevent other code from modifying the controller via other non-const references. If there were later uses that modify the controller through cntr or pass it to APIs requiring a non-const pointer, then const would not be possible; but in the presented function it is possible and the current code thus violates Rule 8.13.
